  URL https://www.ehcache.org/documentation/2.8/get-started/getting-started.html LEN 11872
  transaction :  configure the cache for write-through or write-behind. A write-through cache writes data to the system-of-record in the same thread of execution, therefore in the common scenario of using a database transaction in context of the thread, the write to the database is covered by the transaction in scope. More details (including configuration settings) can be found in the User Guide chapter on Write-through and Write-behind Caching . write-behind The write-behind pattern changes the timing of the write to the system-of-record. Rather than writing to the System of Record in the same thread of execution, write-behind queues the data for write at a later time. The consequences of the change from w
  
  URL https://www.ehcache.org/documentation/2.8/apis/transactions.html LEN 20161
  transaction : e 2) News & Events Ehcache Blog --> Docs Overview Getting Started Configuration BigMemory Auto Resource Control (ARC) APIs Operations Replication Modules Integrations Recipes Code Samples FAQ JavaDoc Transactions in Ehcache Transactions in Ehcache Introduction When to use transactional modes Requirements Configuration Global Transactions Failure Recovery Sample Apps Transaction Managers Local Transactions Performance FAQ Introduction Transactions are supported in versions of Ehcache 2.0 and higher. The 2.3.x or lower releases only support XA. However since ehcache 2.4 support for both Global Transactions with xa_strict and xa modes, and Local Transactions with local mode has been added. All 
  JTA : when a cache contains data calculated out of other cached data. xa Use this mode when you cache data from other data stores (eg: DBMS, JMS) and want to do it in an atomic way under the control of the JTA API but don’t want to pay the price of full two-phase commit. In this mode, your cached data can get out of sync with the other resources participating in the transactions in case of a crash so only use it if you can afford to live with stale data for a brief period of time. xa_strict Same as xa but use it only if you need strict XA disaster recovery guarantees. In this mode, the cached data can never get out of sync with the other resources participating in the transactions, even in case of
  CacheManager :  Spring or EJB where the container rather than managing it themselves, it clearly shows what is going on. The following snippet from our SimpleTX servlet shows a complete transaction. Ehcache cache = cacheManager.getEhcache("xaCache"); UserTransaction ut = getUserTransaction(); printLine(servletResponse, "Hello..."); try { ut.begin(); int index = serviceWithinTx(servletResponse, cache); printLine(servletResponse, "Bye #" + index); ut.commit(); } catch(Exception e) { printLine(servletResponse, "Caught a " + e.getClass() + "! Rolling Tx back"); if(!printStackTrace) { PrintWriter s = servletResponse.getWriter(); e.printStackTrace(s); s.flush(); "/&gt; rollbackTransaction(ut); "/&gt; The source 
